      "solution": "import sys\nimport math\n\n# Auto-generated code below aims at helping you parse\n# the standard input according to the problem statement.\n\nlimit = int(input())\n\n# Write an answer using print\n# To debug: print(\"Debug messages...\", file=sys.stderr, flush=True)\n\ncache={}\ndef collatz(val):\n    n=val\n    count=1\n    while n!=1:\n        if n in cache:\n            temp=count+cache[n]-1\n            cache[val]=temp\n            return temp\n        if n%2==0: n//=2\n        else: n=n*3+1\n        count+=1\n    cache[val]=count\n    return count\n\n\nlast=place=length=0\n\n\nfor i in range(1,limit):\n\n    tempLength=collatz(i)\n    length=max(length,tempLength)\n    if last!=length:\n        last=length\n        place=i\n\nprint(place,length)",
      "statement": "The Collatz conjecture is a conjecture in mathematics that concerns a sequence defined as follows: \n\nCollatz(n) = {\n  stop if n is 1\n  if n is even, return n / 2\n  if n is odd, return 3*n + 1\n}\n\nThe conjecture is that no matter what value of n, the sequence will always reach 1.\n\nThe task is to find the number producing the longest sequence up to a given limit and the length of the sequence.\n\nThe numbers in the sequence might go well over the given limit before they finally reach 1!",
